I have successfully implemented the fix for the Gson-18 issue. Here's a summary of what was accomplished:

## Issue Analysis
The Gson-18 bug was in the `resolve` method of `$Gson$Types.java`, specifically in the wildcard type handling section. The problem was with the control flow using `else if` when checking lower and upper bounds of wildcard types.

## The Fix
I changed the control structure from:
```java
if (originalLowerBound.length == 1) {
  // ... resolve lower bound
} else if (originalUpperBound.length == 1) {
  // ... resolve upper bound  
}
```

To:
```java
if (originalLowerBound.length == 1) {
  // ... resolve lower bound
}
if (originalUpperBound.length == 1) {
  // ... resolve upper bound
}
```

## Why This Fixes Gson-18
- In the original code, if a lower bound existed but didn't change after resolution, and an upper bound also existed and did change, the upper bound would not be processed due to the `else if` structure
- The fix ensures both bounds are checked independently, allowing proper resolution of wildcard types in complex generic scenarios
- This addresses the core issue where `Map<String, ? extends List<SomeClass>>` structures weren't being handled correctly during deserialization

